{
  "integrative": {
    "title": "Integrative Close: Technical Datasheet Analysis",
    "objective": "Differentiate between closely related electrical quantities and assign the correct SI unit and symbol to each in a practical context.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "To be a competent electrician, you must distinguish between quantities that sound similar but represent different physical properties. Using the wrong unit on a specification sheet can lead to incorrect cable sizing or equipment failure.",
      "Key distinctions include the difference between 'Power' (the rate of doing work) and 'Energy' (the total work done over time). You must also separate 'Resistance' (the opposition provided by a specific component) from 'Resistivity' (the inherent property of the material itself, such as copper).",
      "Finally, remember that while Resistance and Impedance both oppose current, they are used in different circuit contexts, yet they share the same SI unit."
    ],
    "questionText": "A motor's technical specification requires you to identify four distinct values. Provide the SI unit name and the correct symbol for each of the following: \n1. The rate at which the motor converts electrical energy into mechanical work. \n2. The total amount of work performed by the motor during a full shift. \n3. The total opposition to current flow within the motor's AC circuit. \n4. The specific electrical property of the copper material used in the motor windings.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "1. Power: Watt (W)",
      "2. Energy: Joule (J)",
      "3. Impedance: Ohm (Ω)",
      "4. Resistivity: Ohm-metre (Ωm)"
    ],
    "hint": "Think about which quantity describes a 'rate' versus a 'total,' and remember that resistivity is a material property measured over a distance (metre)."
  }
}

